{{Infobox U.S. legislation | shorttitle = Anti-Heroin Act of 1924 | othershorttitles = | longtitle = An Act prohibiting the importation of crude opium for the purpose of manufacturing heroin. | colloquialacronym = | nickname = Opium Importation Prohibition Act of 1924 | enacted by = 68th | effective date = June 7, 1924 | public law url = http://legisworks.org/congress/68/publaw-274.pdf | cite public law = 68-274 | cite statutes at large = {{usstat|43|657}} | acts amended = | acts repealed = | title amended = [[Title 21 of the United States Code|21 U.S.C.: Food and Drugs]] | sections created = <!--{{USC}} can be used--> | sections amended = {{Usc-title-chap|21|6}} § 173 | leghisturl = | introducedin = House | introducedbill = {{USBill|68|H.R.|7079}} | introducedby = [[Stephen G. Porter]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]–[[Pennsylvania|PA]]) | introduceddate = April 17, 1924 | committees = [[United States House Committee on Ways and Means|House Ways and Means]] | passedbody1 = House | passeddate1 = April 21, 1924 | passedvote1 = Passed | passedbody2 = Senate | passedas2 = <!-- used if the second body changes the name of the legislation --> | passeddate2 = May 27, 1924 | passedvote2 = Passed | conferencedate = | passedbody3 = | passeddate3 = | passedvote3 = | agreedbody3 = <!-- used when the other body agrees without going into committee --> | agreeddate3 = <!-- used when the other body agrees without going into committee --> | agreedvote3 = <!-- used when the other body agrees without going into committee --> | agreedbody4 = <!-- used if agreedbody3 further amends legislation --> | agreeddate4 = <!-- used if agreedbody3 further amends legislation --> | agreedvote4 = <!-- used if agreedbody3 further amends legislation --> | passedbody4 = | passeddate4 = | passedvote4 = | signedpresident = [[Calvin Coolidge]] | signeddate = June 7, 1924 | unsignedpresident = <!-- used when passed without presidential signing --> | unsigneddate = <!-- used when passed without presidential signing --> | vetoedpresident = <!-- used when passed by overriding presidential veto --> | vetoeddate = <!-- used when passed by overriding presidential veto --> | overriddenbody1 = <!-- used when passed by overriding presidential veto --> | overriddendate1 = <!-- used when passed by overriding presidential veto --> | overriddenvote1 = <!-- used when passed by overriding presidential veto --> | overriddenbody2 = <!-- used when passed by overriding presidential veto --> | overriddendate2 = <!-- used when passed by overriding presidential veto --> | overriddenvote2 = <!-- used when passed by overriding presidential veto --> | amendments = | SCOTUS cases = }} '''Anti-Heroin Act of 1924''' is a [[Law of the United States|United States federal law]] prohibiting the importation and possession of [[opium]] for the [[chemical synthesis]] of an [[Addiction|addictive]] [[narcotic]] known as diamorphine or [[heroin]]. The [[Act of Congress]] amended the Smoking Opium Exclusion Act of 1909 which authorized the importation of the [[Poppy (flower)|poppy]] [[Papaver somniferum|plant]] for medicinal purposes utilizing an [[opium pipe]] or [[Opium lamp|vaporization]] to consume the [[Euphoria|euphoric]] [[opiate]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://legisworks.org/congress/60/publaw-221.pdf |title=Smoking Opium Exclusion Act of 1909 - P.L. 60-221 |work=35 Stat. 614 ~ House Bill 27427 |date=February 9, 1909 |publisher=Legis★Works}}</ref>
The H.R. 7079 [[Bill (law)|legislation]] was passed by the 68th United States Congressional session and enacted into law by the 30th President of the United States Calvin Coolidge on June 7, 1924.
==Repeal of Anti-Heroin Act== The 1924 [[Public law|United States public law]] was repealed by the enactment of [[Comprehensive Drug Abuse Prevention and Control Act of 1970|Comprehensive Drug Abuse Prevention and Control Act]] on October 27, 1970.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/USCODE-2015-title21/pdf/USCODE-2015-title21-chap13-subchapII.pdf |title=21 U.S.C. ~ Subchapter II - Import and Export § 952 |work=Title 21 - Food and Drugs ~ Chapter 13 - Drug Abuse Prevention and Control |publisher=U.S. Government Publishing Office}}</ref>
==World Conference on Narcotic Education== [[File:GlycoHeroin.jpg|thumb|100px|left]] The [[League of Nations]] and [[United States]] began participating in world narcotic conferences in the early 1900s. In 1924, United States House of Representatives passed a [[Resolution (law)|resolution]] for international conferences better known as [[International Opium Convention|The Hague Opium Convention]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://legisworks.org/congress/68/pubres-20.pdf |title=Opium and Narcotic Drugs Control Conferences ~ Public Resolution 68-20 |date=May 15, 1924 |series=43 Stat. 119 ~ House Joint Resolution 195 |publisher= Legis★Works}}</ref>
In 1926, [[69th United States Congress]] held hearings on a House resolution for the United States participation in the first narcotic education conference to be conducted in [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]] from July 5 to July 9, 1926.<ref>{{cite book |last=Middlemiss |first=Herbert Samuel |year=1926 |title=Narcotic Education: Proceedings of the First World Conference on Narcotic Education, July 5-9, 1926, Philadelphia |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=H.S. Middlemiss |pages=1-403 |oclc=2736915}}</ref>
In the early 1930s, the World Conference on Narcotic Education meetings were held at the [[Hotel McAlpin]] in [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]] where the [[Presidency of Herbert Hoover|31st President of the United States]] Herbert Hoover issued public statements stressing narcotic drugs as a "fearful menace" and a "menace to society".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/?pid=22523 |title=Herbert Hoover: "Message to the World Conference on Narcotic Education.," February 21, 1930 |author1=Peters, Gerhard |author2=Woolley, John T |publisher = University of California - Santa Barbara |work= The American Presidency Project}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/?pid=22987 |title=Herbert Hoover: "Message to the World Conference on Narcotic Education.," February 20, 1931 |author1=Peters, Gerhard |author2=Woolley, John T |publisher = University of California - Santa Barbara |work= The American Presidency Project}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/?pid=23451 |title=Herbert Hoover: "Message to the World Conference on Narcotic Education.," February 18, 1932 |author1=Peters, Gerhard |author2=Woolley, John T |publisher = University of California - Santa Barbara |work= The American Presidency Project}}</ref>
